const DEALHAWK_KNOWLEDGE: StarterKnowledgeTemplate[] = [
  // Creative finance playbooks (7)
  {
    category: "processes",
    title: "Subject-To step-by-step acquisition guide",
    contentTemplate:
      "The Sub-To closing playbook for {{businessName}}. 1) Seller qualification (existing rate < 5%, PITI < market rent by 20%+, balance/ARV < 85%, seller prioritizes credit over cash). 2) Paperwork minimums: Purchase agreement with Sub-To language, Sub-To disclosure (seller acknowledges DOS risk + loan stays in their name), Limited POA, performance agreement, authorization to release info. 3) Closing mechanics: title company that has closed Sub-To before (not every title co will), land trust often used for privacy and DOS camouflage. 4) Post-close: ACH mortgage auto-pay from operator's account, insurance restructured with operator / trust as primary insured, operator takes possession. 5) Non-negotiables: attorney licensed in the property's state reviews every document before signing."
  },
  {
    category: "processes",
    title: "Novation partnership agreement framework",
    contentTemplate:
      "Novation for {{businessName}}. A three-party agreement where a new buyer replaces the original buyer on the original contract. Used when the wholesaler partners with the seller to list the property, rehab it lightly, and sell at retail — splitting the upside. Structure: 1) Original purchase contract executed at low wholesale number. 2) Novation agreement adds the retail-buyer scenario with an upside split. 3) Seller covers or finances light rehab. 4) Retail listing, new buyer replaces the wholesaler on the contract. 5) Upside distributed per the novation split. Key: seller must understand they're giving up the certainty of the wholesale close for a higher expected value at more risk. Attorney review required."
  },
  {
    category: "processes",
    title: "Wraparound mortgage deal structure and math",
    contentTemplate:
      "Wraparound mortgages for {{businessName}}. Seller keeps the original mortgage in place; creates a new, larger mortgage to the buyer at a higher rate. Buyer makes one payment to the seller; seller makes the underlying payment and pockets the spread. Example: original $140K loan at 3.1%, buyer takes a $180K wrap at 7%. Buyer's payment on $180K at 7% is much higher than the $140K at 3.1% payment — the spread is the seller's monthly income on the wrap. Risks: (1) buyer default cascades to seller's credit, (2) DOS on the underlying loan if the lender notices transfer, (3) state-specific restrictions on wraparound mortgages. Use when: seller has equity they want to extract as a stream, buyer can't qualify for a traditional loan."
  },
  {
    category: "processes",
    title: "Seller carry structures (owner financing) — 1st, 2nd, split",
    contentTemplate:
      "Seller-carry for {{businessName}}. Seller becomes the lender. 1st-position carry: seller holds the primary lien, no bank involved. Used when seller owns free-and-clear. 2nd-position carry: seller holds junior lien behind a bank loan. Used to close the gap between bank loan-to-value and purchase price. Split: seller carries a portion (e.g., 10%) to help buyer qualify for the bank loan on the balance. Dodd-Frank applies if the property is owner-occupied consumer residence and the seller has made 4+ such loans in the year — triggers consumer-protection requirements. Document: promissory note, deed of trust / mortgage, servicing agreement. Attorney review required."
  },
  {
    category: "policies",
    title: "Due-on-sale (DOS) clause mitigation framework",
    contentTemplate:
      "DOS mitigation for {{businessName}}. The DOS clause (12 U.S.C. § 1701j-3, Garn-St. Germain Act) gives the lender the right to call the loan due when title transfers. In practice: rare on performing loans (lender cost to foreclose ~$40–50K; they prefer receiving payments). Mitigations: (1) Land trust — title goes into a trust (Garn-St. Germain exempts transfers to inter-vivos trusts where the borrower remains beneficiary). This is a gray area if the operator is the beneficiary; consult attorney. (2) Keep loan performing — on-time payments are the single strongest DOS avoider. (3) Operator-owned escrow — keep 6+ months of payments in escrow at closing to guarantee performance if cashflow disrupts. (4) Insurance correctly structured — policy names the title-holding entity as primary insured; a mismatch is a DOS red flag the lender may notice. (5) Do NOT tell the lender. Not legal advice — attorney review required before using any mitigation."
  },
  {
    category: "policies",
    title: "Land trust basics (with DOS / privacy disclaimers)",
    contentTemplate:
      "Land trusts for {{businessName}}. A land trust is a revocable trust that holds legal title to real estate with a named trustee; the beneficiary is the person with actual ownership interest. Used in Sub-To for (a) privacy — the public record shows the trust name, not the operator's name, and (b) DOS camouflage — the Garn-St. Germain Act explicitly exempts transfers to an inter-vivos trust where the borrower remains a beneficiary. Catch: in a Sub-To, the borrower (seller) is typically NOT the ongoing beneficiary after closing — the operator is. That's a gray zone. Some attorneys structure the trust with the seller as a co-beneficiary for a short period to preserve the exemption; others consider that a sham and risky. State law varies. Attorney review required before using land trusts as DOS mitigation."
  },
  {
    category: "processes",
    title: "Lease-option structures and when to use them",
    contentTemplate:
      "Lease-options for {{businessName}}. The buyer is technically a tenant with an option to purchase at a pre-agreed price during a pre-agreed window. Seller keeps title, tax benefits, and depreciation. If the 'buyer' defaults, eviction is far faster than foreclosure (weeks vs. months/years). Structure: lease agreement + separate option agreement + non-refundable option fee (3–5% of purchase price typical) + rent credit (portion of monthly rent applied to purchase price). Use when: seller is risk-averse about Sub-To DOS risk, buyer needs time to qualify for financing, market rent supports cashflow. Risk: in some states (Texas notably), too-long lease-options can be reclassified as an executory contract and trigger consumer-protection requirements. Attorney review required."
  },

  // Wholesale & flip (6)
  {
    category: "processes",
    title: "MAO formula variations (70% rule, market-adjusted, full cost-build)",
    contentTemplate:
      "MAO variations for {{businessName}}. (1) Standard 70% rule: MAO = (ARV × 0.70) − rehab. Works for flips in normal markets. (2) Market-adjusted: 65% for < $100K ARV (fixed costs don't scale down), 75–80% in tight-inventory markets where flippers are paying up. (3) Full cost-build MAO: MAO = ARV − rehab − holding_costs (6 months of taxes + insurance + utilities + HOA) − financing_costs (interest on hard-money at 10–12%) − seller_concessions (2–3%) − realtor_commission (6%) − closing_costs (both sides, 3–4%) − desired_profit (15–20% of ARV). Full cost-build is the honest number. (4) BRRRR MAO: driven by rent × 12 × 5 ÷ (rehab + acquisition). (5) Sub-To price: a DIFFERENT math entirely — acquisition = loan_balance + moving-money to seller; success measured by cashflow + rate-preservation, not MAO. Always compute all four and surface the winner."
  },
  {
    category: "processes",
    title: "Assignment contract vs. double close — when to use each",
    contentTemplate:
      "Assignment vs. double close for {{businessName}}. Assignment: wholesaler signs purchase agreement with seller, then assigns the contract to an end buyer for an assignment fee. One closing. Cheaper. Disclosure of assignment fee may be required in some states. Double close: wholesaler closes with the seller, then immediately closes with the end buyer on the same day or same week. Two closings, two sets of closing costs. The wholesaler briefly takes title. Why double-close instead of assign: (1) strict-disclosure states (IL, OK, SC, PA) where wholesaler-licensing or assignment-fee-disclosure requirements make assignment painful, (2) assignment fee is > 10% of deal price (some end buyers refuse to see that on the HUD), (3) seller's lender prohibits assignment in the original loan docs. Rule: assign in permissive states under 10% fee, double-close in strict states or over 10% fee."
  },
  {
    category: "processes",
    title: "Virtual wholesaling SOP (remote / out-of-state)",
    contentTemplate:
      "Virtual wholesaling for {{businessName}}. Wholesaling markets you don't live in. Requirements: (1) local title company / closing attorney who has worked with virtual wholesalers before — essential. (2) Local buyer list — the single biggest gap; build via Buyer List Builder + REI club scraping. (3) Boots-on-ground for photos and inspection — pay $50–100 per property to a local contractor / photographer. (4) State-specific wholesaler / licensing compliance — check KB state matrix for every market. (5) Market selection: path-of-progress tertiary markets with lower investor competition and higher assignment fees, avoid HCOL coastal markets where margins are compressed. (6) Virtual-call best practice: video call with the seller builds trust better than phone; offer but don't insist."
  },
  {
    category: "processes",
    title: "Building cash buyer lists — 12 proven sources",
    contentTemplate:
      "Cash-buyer sources for {{businessName}}. (1) Recent cash-sale records from county deed transfers — single strongest source. (2) REI club member lists. (3) LLC-entity resolution on deeds — an LLC closing 3+ cash deals per year is a flipper or landlord. (4) BiggerPockets forums + local RE Facebook groups. (5) Craigslist 'I buy houses' ads (they ARE the buyers). (6) Google 'we buy houses [city]' top ads. (7) Zillow 'make me move' and expired-FSBO listings (often held by flippers). (8) Hard-money lender client lists (ask your HML who their most active borrowers are). (9) Title company investor lists (ask which buyers they close most often). (10) Mortgage broker DSCR-loan pipelines. (11) Wholesaler-to-wholesaler network trading. (12) Disposition blast opt-ins from prior deals — a buyer who bought from you once will buy again."
  },
  {
    category: "processes",
    title: "Wholesale contract templates (purchase agreement + assignment)",
    contentTemplate:
      "Contract templates for {{businessName}}. Purchase agreement with the seller: includes 'and / or assigns' language next to the buyer name, 10–14 day inspection period, title contingency, financing contingency (even if paying cash — preserves exit), earnest money escrowed with a title company (never handed to the seller directly), specific performance clause favors the buyer. Assignment contract with the end buyer: specifies the original PA terms being assigned, the assignment fee, the closing date (mirrored from the PA), the buyer's non-refundable assignment deposit ($1K–$5K typical) that's applied at closing. ALL templates must be state-specific — use attorney-drafted templates for every state the operator closes in. Never copy templates from the internet blindly; state requirements vary."
  },
  {
    category: "processes",
    title: "Earnest money strategies (protecting $100–$500 EMD)",
    contentTemplate:
      "Earnest money for {{businessName}}. Goal: protect the EMD if the deal falls through, while offering enough to signal seriousness to the seller. Best practices: (1) Escrow with a title company, never to the seller. (2) Amount: $500–$1,000 on wholesale deals (tiny compared to traditional real estate's 1–3% of purchase price; most sellers accept when the contract explains EMD is customary for investor purchases). (3) Inspection contingency: 10–14 days during which EMD is fully refundable. This is the operator's escape hatch if due diligence turns up a problem or the deal can't be assigned. (4) Title contingency: refundable if title is not marketable. (5) Financing contingency even on cash deals: preserves a fallback exit. (6) Never risk EMD above $500 in the first 72 hours of a deal — that's when the Comp Analyst and Sub-To Qualifier are still running."
  },

  // Seller psychology & scripts (5)
  {
    category: "processes",
    title: "Pre-foreclosure conversation framework (empathy-first)",
    contentTemplate:
      "Pre-foreclosure script framework for {{businessName}}. Core principle: the seller is in distress and every other wholesaler is calling them. The winning wedge is empathy + credit protection + rate preservation. Opening: never reference the NOD filing. Lead with 'I'm reaching out because I work with homeowners in [city] who are thinking about their options — did I catch you at a bad time?' Build rapport 2–3 minutes before any offer discussion. Position: 'My goal is to see if there's a path that protects your credit, avoids a foreclosure on your record, and gets you cash to walk away.' If seller shares they're behind: 'I'm sorry. Would it help if I walked you through what the options actually look like, with no pressure?' Never promise the bank won't foreclose. Never promise credit outcomes. Offer an attorney consultation on the Sub-To path."
  },
  {
    category: "processes",
    title: "Tired landlord scripts",
    contentTemplate:
      "Tired-landlord scripts for {{businessName}}. Core wedge: the pain the landlord already feels (tenants, maintenance, vacancy, out-of-state management). SMS opener: 'Hi [Name], are you still renting out [address]? Interested in cashing out if we could handle the whole process?' Pulls the yes-response first. Follow-up after yes: 'Great — I work with a small group of buyers in [city] focused on tired-landlord situations. Would you be open to a 5-minute call about what you'd want in a clean exit?' On the call: four qualifying questions (condition, timeline, reason, price expectations). Close or schedule follow-up. Position as 'we handle tenants, repairs, and the whole closing' — the landlord's pain points all at once."
  },
  {
    category: "processes",
    title: "Probate / inherited property sensitivity guide",
    contentTemplate:
      "Probate script guide for {{businessName}}. Core rule: NEVER reference the probate filing. The heirs often don't know public records show the filing; feeling surveilled destroys trust. Reach the executor (name in filing) indirectly — letter first, then a polite phone call saying 'I work with families in [city] who have inherited property and are figuring out what to do with it.' First call is NOT about buying. It's about asking what they've decided, offering to answer questions about the process (listing vs. selling as-is vs. holding as a rental), and scheduling a follow-up. Offer discussion happens in call 2 or 3, only after rapport is real. Never pressure. Heirs often need time to make a decision and the wholesaler who waits wins."
  },
  {
    category: "processes",
    title: "Divorce situation protocol (avoid becoming leverage between parties)",
    contentTemplate:
      "Divorce protocol for {{businessName}}. NEVER take sides. NEVER reference the divorce filing. NEVER become a leverage point one spouse uses against the other. Reach out to whichever spouse's name is on the tax assessor record (often both). Script: 'I'm reaching out about the house at [address] — are you considering your options for it?' If the seller volunteers the divorce context, respond with empathy but zero sides: 'I'm sorry you're going through that. My role is to help you get a clean exit if that's what both of you decide makes sense.' Always require BOTH spouses to sign the purchase agreement and the disclosure (even if only one is on title — court may require both signatures on a marital asset). Offer a clean quick-close as the wedge: many divorcing couples are under a court-ordered sale timeline. Do not close until the divorce attorney has cleared the sale."
  },
  {
    category: "processes",
    title: "Handling the 'what's your offer?' objection",
    contentTemplate:
      "'What's your offer?' handling for {{businessName}}. Wrong answer: give a number. Right answer: turn it back with context. Script: 'Before I give you a number, help me understand what would need to be true for this to work for you — what would make it a good outcome?' Most sellers answer with a price range and timeline that's lower than the operator feared. If the seller insists: 'Fair enough. Without having seen the property in person, the range that's realistic in this market for properties in similar condition is between $X and $Y. If I walked the property and the condition is what we've discussed, I could be in that range. Would that be something you'd want to explore?' Never give a point number over the phone before seeing the property. Never give an offer without a 14-day inspection contingency."
  },

  // Market intelligence (4)
  {
    category: "about_business",
    title: "How to read a market cycle (wholesale-friendly vs. creative-finance-friendly)",
    contentTemplate:
      "Market cycle reading for {{businessName}}. Wholesale-friendly market indicators: rising inventory (DOM climbing), price-drops per listing climbing, cash-buyer activity strong, new-listing volume up, and a distressed-seller pipeline (NODs, tax delinquencies). Creative-finance-friendly market indicators: ~80% of mortgages at sub-6% rates (the 2026 reality), rising rates widening the gap between inherited rates and current rates, inventory rising but sellers resistant to listing (rate-lock). The 2026 playbook: both conditions co-exist. Wholesale margins compress as cash-buyer competition intensifies, but the creative-finance TAM explodes because ~80% of mortgage holders have rates the market would pay to inherit. Rule: in cold markets favor wholesale + fix-flip; in hot markets favor Sub-To + creative; in 2026's mixed-signal market, underwrite both per deal and pick the winner."
  },
  {
    category: "about_business",
    title: "Path-of-progress neighborhood identification",
    contentTemplate:
      "Path-of-progress for {{businessName}}. Path-of-progress zips are the zips where the money hasn't arrived yet but will. Indicators: (1) adjacent to a gentrifying zip (comps rising 10%+ YoY while subject zip is flat), (2) infrastructure investment (new transit, new stadium, new corporate relocation announced), (3) rising owner-occupant share (rentals converting to owner-occupied), (4) school-district rating improving year over year, (5) cash-buyer activity concentrating (flippers spotting the signal first). Path-of-progress is where BRRRR and fix-and-flip win — you buy at old-neighborhood prices and exit at gentrified-neighborhood prices 18–36 months later. Path-of-stagnation is the opposite and should be avoided for long-holds, but may still work for wholesale."
  },
  {
    category: "about_business",
    title: "Rental demand signals for BRRRR viability",
    contentTemplate:
      "BRRRR rental-demand signals for {{businessName}}. Before a BRRRR, verify: (1) Rent-to-price ratio (monthly rent / purchase price) >= 1% — below 1% and BRRRR cashflow breaks. (2) Vacancy rate < 8% (Census ACS data). (3) Days-on-market for rentals < 30 days (Zillow rentals dashboard). (4) Section-8 payment standards in the zip — HUD publishes fair-market-rent tables; a zip with FMR above market rent indicates Section-8 viable. (5) Jobs within a 30-minute commute. (6) School district rating 5+ if targeting family rentals. (7) Historical rent growth 3–5% YoY (not flat, not spiking — spikes revert). Avoid: rural zips with rent < 0.8% of price (cashflow rarely works), college-town rentals (seasonality + wear), or zips with population decline > 1% YoY."
  },
  {
    category: "processes",
    title: "Decision tree: BRRRR vs flip vs wholesale vs Sub-To",
    contentTemplate:
      "Exit-strategy decision tree for {{businessName}}. Start with the Comp Analyst's four MAOs and the Sub-To Qualifier output. Rules: (1) If seller has loan rate < 5% AND PITI < market rent by 20%+ AND balance/ARV < 85% → Sub-To is the winning exit (unless DOS risk is flagged high by Sub-To Qualifier). (2) Else if Wholesale MAO > seller's minimum + $5K spread AND market is cold → Wholesale. (3) Else if BRRRR MAO penciled AND rent-to-price >= 1% AND operator has long-hold capital → BRRRR. (4) Else if Flip MAO penciled AND operator has flip crew + capital → Fix-and-flip. (5) Else if none of the above pencil but seller motivation is 70+/100 → Creative Finance Architect designs a bespoke structure (novation, wrap, lease-option, hybrid). (6) Else decline politely and route to the 90-day revival queue."
  },

  // Legal & ethical (5)
  {
    category: "policies",
    title: "State-by-state wholesaling legality (all 50)",
    contentTemplate:
      "Wholesaling legality matrix for {{businessName}}. This KB article is maintained as the source-of-truth for every state's wholesaling requirements. General principle: a wholesaler markets their equitable interest in the contract, NOT the underlying property. Marketing the property without a license = unlicensed real-estate brokerage in most states. Strict-disclosure or registration states as of 2025–2026 include: Illinois (capped unlicensed assignments per year, disclosure required), Oklahoma (licensing required for repeat wholesalers), Pennsylvania (disclosure of wholesaler intent required), South Carolina (investor-intent disclosure required), Maryland (wholesaler disclosure to buyer required under recent 2024 updates), Virginia (expanded disclosure requirements under 2025 updates), Tennessee (specific contract-assignment disclosure required). Each state's full rule set is tracked in the maintained matrix. Operator: confirm current rules with a state-licensed real-estate attorney before your first transaction in any new state. 50-state detail is populated during Phase 7 (Legal firewall) of the template build."
  },
  {
    category: "policies",
    title: "Required disclosures — the equitable-interest disclosure",
    contentTemplate:
      "Equitable-interest disclosure for {{businessName}}. The single most important compliance fact: a wholesaler markets their equitable interest in a contract, NOT the underlying property. If the operator markets the property itself without a license, it's unlicensed real-estate brokerage. If they market the contract (and use private buyer lists), it's investor activity as a principal. Required disclosure language in disposition: 'I have an equitable interest in a contract to purchase a property located at [general area]. I am marketing my contract rights, not the property itself. I am not a licensed real-estate broker.' Every disposition email, Facebook post, and buyer-list blast must include a variant of this language. The Disposition Agent auto-inserts this. Double-close workaround for strict states: because the wholesaler briefly takes title, they can market the property during their brief ownership — at the cost of two sets of closing costs."
  },
  {
    category: "policies",
    title: "When you need a real-estate license (state-by-state)",
    contentTemplate:
      "Licensing-required conditions for {{businessName}}. General rule: an individual acting as a principal in a single transaction (buying or selling their own interest) does NOT need a license in any state. An individual brokering transactions for others (marketing someone else's property, taking commissions) needs a license in every state. The gray zone: a wholesaler who does 5+ assignments per year starts to look like a broker to state regulators. Strict states (Illinois, Oklahoma, recently) have codified this by capping unlicensed assignments per year, requiring investor registration, or requiring disclosure of wholesaler status. Safe pattern: treat every deal as principal activity, market only the contract (not the property), work through a real-estate attorney in every state, and consider getting licensed if doing 10+ deals/year in any one state. Not legal advice."
  },
  {
    category: "policies",
    title: "Ethical Sub-To practices (how not to harm distressed sellers)",
    contentTemplate:
      "Sub-To ethics for {{businessName}}. Sub-To transfers title to the operator while leaving the loan in the seller's name. If the operator stops paying, the seller's credit is destroyed and they may face foreclosure on a home they no longer own. This is the single biggest ethical landmine. Non-negotiable ethical practices: (1) Full transparency with the seller — DOS risk is disclosed, the seller's liability if the operator defaults is disclosed, in writing and signed. (2) Operator-funded attorney for the seller — the operator pays for the seller's attorney to review the Sub-To documents independently (conflict-of-interest free review). (3) Escrow of 6+ months of payments at closing so the seller has protection if cashflow disrupts. (4) Performance agreement that specifies what happens if the operator defaults (typically: seller can re-record title and re-take possession). (5) Annual statement to the seller showing loan balance, payment history, taxes, insurance. (6) Never Sub-To a seller who is elderly, cognitively impaired, in active grief, or without fully understanding the DOS risk."
  },
  {
    category: "policies",
    title: "Contract contingencies that protect the wholesaler",
    contentTemplate:
      "Wholesaler contingencies for {{businessName}}. Every purchase agreement must include: (1) Inspection contingency — 10–14 day period during which the buyer can back out for any reason; the EMD is fully refundable. This is the operator's escape hatch. (2) Title contingency — refundable if title defects make the property non-marketable. (3) Financing contingency — refundable if buyer financing falls through (even if paying cash, this preserves an exit). (4) 'And/or assigns' buyer line — allows assignment without renegotiation. (5) Specific performance favors the buyer — if the seller backs out after the inspection period, buyer can compel closing or collect damages. (6) Closing date with 30–45 day window from PA signing. (7) Attorney review clause in the states where that's a right (NJ, NY, IL). All templates should be drafted by a state-licensed attorney; the above is the minimum feature-set."
  },

  // Deal documentation (1 — library)
  {
    category: "custom",
    title: "Deal documentation library (contracts + disclosures)",
    contentTemplate:
      "Deal documentation library for {{businessName}}. This entry catalogs every contract and disclosure template the desk maintains. All templates must be state-specific and attorney-drafted — generic templates are a liability. Library contents: (1) Purchase agreement (per state). (2) Assignment of contract (per state). (3) JV / partnership agreement for novation. (4) Sub-To disclosure (per state) — seller acknowledges DOS risk and that the loan stays in their name. (5) Authorization to release information — lets the operator talk to the seller's lender. (6) Limited power of attorney — handles mortgage-related matters post-closing. (7) Sub-To performance agreement — specifies what happens if the operator defaults on payments. (8) Buyer's checklist — what an end buyer should verify before signing an assignment. (9) State-specific wholesaler disclosure (per state). (10) Equitable-interest disclosure for disposition. Operator: populate and maintain this library with state-licensed attorney-drafted templates only."
  },

  // ── HMHW operational layer (12) ──────────────────────────────────────
  // Rolled in from the Hold My Hand Wholesale courses (Richard Taylor):
  // conversational architecture, deterministic underwriting heuristics,
  // and trust-acquisition seller-protection language that Dealhawk's
  // agent mesh was thin on. Existing Sub-To / DOS / wholesale entries
  // are unchanged; these are the operational layer on top.
  {
    category: "processes",
    title: "Pitch architecture — Checkmate (seller finance) + Trojan Horse (MT)",
    contentTemplate:
      "The pitch architecture for {{businessName}}. Two near-identical conversational moves that turn 'no' into yes. Both start by REFUSING to pitch creative finance and end with creative finance as the agent's only remaining option.\n\n## The core rule\nNobody wants seller finance. Nobody wants their mortgage taken over. If you open with 'will the seller seller-finance?' or 'can I take over your mortgage?' the listing agent will reject you 95% of the time. Your job is to call about a NORMAL purchase, walk the agent through why every normal path fails, and let creative finance arrive as the SOLUTION TO A PROBLEM THE AGENT JUST NAMED.\n\n## Checkmate Pitch — for seller finance on properties that don't cash flow\n1. **Open at asking** (or near asking — within ~5%). 'Hey, I'm calling about [address]. I may be interested at or near asking. I just need to understand how the numbers work.'\n2. **Ask the rent / income question.** 'What is the property currently bringing in per month?' Then: 'Actual rent or projected?' Always anchor on actual.\n3. **Demonstrate the DSCR fail.** 'Based on what it's bringing in, a normal investor loan payment on this price would be ~$X. After taxes, insurance, vacancy, repairs, management, the property loses money each month. A DSCR-style investor loan legally can't qualify a borrower on negative cash flow — that's a predatory loan.' See `dscr_loan_walkthrough_for_agents` for the long version.\n4. **Walk the three buyer types out the door.**\n   - **Loan buyer:** can't qualify at this price because the property doesn't cash flow.\n   - **Cash buyer:** would need a 20–30% discount because the stock market returns 10% passively — buying real estate that returns less and requires management is irrational.\n   - **Lowball buyer:** seller has already said no to lower offers.\n5. **Present seller finance as the only remaining path.** 'The only way I see to get close to your seller's number is to structure payments. I could offer [price at or above asking], [down] down, monthly [payment], balloon in [N] years.'\n6. **Mention agent commission upfront — this is the lubricant.** 'We can also make sure your commission is paid upfront at closing.' Most agent objections evaporate once their fee is secured.\n\n## Trojan Horse Pitch — for mortgage takeover on low-equity properties\n1. **Open with a normal cash offer 12–15% below list.** 'Hey, I'm calling about [address]. Would the seller consider $X?' (where X is meaningfully below list).\n2. **Wait for the rejection.** Most listing agents on low-equity properties reject below-asking offers with a tell: 'no, the seller can't go that low because they have a mortgage they need to cover.'\n3. **THAT is the unlock.** Pivot: 'Oh — if the mortgage is close to the list price, would they consider letting us take over the debt instead?' You are now offering MT as a solution to a problem the agent just volunteered.\n4. **Frame the offer as better than a normal sale.** 'I can offer the seller $X to walk away [where X is more than they'd net after realtor fees on a normal sale], pay your commission upfront, and take over the monthly payments. If we ever miss payments, the agreement returns the property to the seller — they're protected.'\n\n## Rules across both pitches\n- **Never argue.** See `never_argue_rule`. The moment you feel you're 'winning' the conversation, you've lost the prospect.\n- **Never explain the trust / wrap / wraparound mechanics in the first call.** Overloading the agent with structure detail kills the call. Save mechanics for call 2 once they're warm.\n- **Always mention the agent's commission is paid upfront.** This is the single most important sentence in either pitch.\n- **Honor dealMode.** In 'research' mode this pitch is for the operator's playbook only — agents do not place these calls. In 'outreach' mode the pitch is live."
  },
  {
    category: "processes",
    title: "DSCR loan walkthrough — how to demonstrate to a listing agent that the property can't sell normally",
    contentTemplate:
      "The DSCR walkthrough for {{businessName}}. Used inside the Checkmate Pitch to demonstrate to a listing agent why their listing isn't selling and why creative finance is the only solution.\n\n## What DSCR means\nDebt Service Coverage Ratio loan. The only loan an investor can get on a non-owner-occupied property. Asset-based, not personal-credit-based. The lender qualifies the loan based on whether the property's income covers the debt service plus a buffer (typically DSCR ≥ 1.20 — income covers payment with 20% headroom).\n\n## Why this matters in the pitch\n- If a property's rent is close to or below what the mortgage payment would be on a 20%-down loan at current rates, **no investor can legally qualify for that loan.** Granting a loan you know will default is a predatory loan and regulated.\n- The property therefore sits on market until either (a) the price drops to where it cash flows, or (b) a creative buyer arrives who doesn't need a new DSCR loan.\n- This explains, in 3 minutes, why a million-dollar multifamily bringing in $7K/month is sitting for 200+ days — it's not the seller, it's not the market, it's that the math LITERALLY DOES NOT QUALIFY for any conventional lender.\n\n## The walkthrough — verbatim talking points\n1. 'The seller's asking $X. Investors on this kind of property put 20% down and get a DSCR loan at current rates around 6.5–7%.'\n2. 'On $X at 7% with taxes and insurance, the monthly payment is about $Y.'\n3. 'The property's currently bringing in $Z per month. After 20% off the top for vacancy and repairs and management, that's $Z×0.8 in real cash.'\n4. 'A DSCR lender legally can't grant a loan where the income doesn't cover the payment by a 1.20 ratio. That's not me — that's how every investor lender qualifies.'\n5. 'So the property can't sell to a normal investor at this price. It either drops to a price where the math works, or the seller takes a creative-finance structure where the math isn't gated by DSCR.'\n6. 'I'd love to buy at your asking price. I just don't see how anyone qualifies at that price the normal way. Want to talk about a structure that does work?'\n\n## Why this lands\nMost listing agents don't actually understand DSCR or why their investment listings sit. When you walk them through it cleanly, you've educated them. Agents tend to trust the educator and present the operator's creative offer to the seller with more credibility.\n\n## What this is NOT\nThis is not legal or financial advice to the seller. The walkthrough is between the operator and the listing agent, explaining why no qualified investor buyer is coming. The seller never hears DSCR — they hear 'the path that gets you the closest to your number.'\n\n## When to use\nMultifamily 5+ unit properties: always (FHA owner-occupant path is blocked above 4 units). Single-family priced above $150K in markets where rent < 1% of price: usually. Cheap properties (<$120K) in cash-flow markets like Memphis / Cleveland / Detroit: rarely — these cash flow even with current rates, the listing's just priced wrong."
  },
  {
    category: "processes",
    title: "Sub-To rate × price matrix — when which down-payment level works",
    contentTemplate:
      "The Sub-To viability matrix for {{businessName}}. Gates `dealhawk_qualify_sub_to` recommendations and the Creative Finance Architect's structure choice. This matrix prevents the most common Sub-To failure mode: pitching a structure that won't find a buyer.\n\n## The grid\n| Property price | Existing rate | Recommended max down payment | Why |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Under $120K | Any rate (2–7%) | 10–15% of price (sometimes higher on $80K boxes) | Cheap properties cash flow regardless of rate. Buyer can stomach a higher entry fee because the cash-on-cash return remains strong. |\n| $120K–$150K | Sub-5% (locked) | 5–10% | Low rate is the asset; entry fee can be moderate. |\n| $120K–$150K | 6–7% | 5% MAX, sometimes $0 | Rate isn't doing the work — entry fee is the whole investor case. |\n| Over $150K | Sub-5% (locked) | 5–10% | The locked rate is grand-slam-worthy. Buyer pays for the rate arbitrage. |\n| Over $150K | 6–7% | $0 down or skip | Nothing makes this worth doing for a third-party buyer. Either you live in it yourself, or you walk. |\n\n## Multifamily 5+ unit modifier\nMultifamily 5+ units are exclusively investor properties (FHA owner-occupant path stops at 4 units). DSCR fail logic applies hard — see `dscr_loan_walkthrough_for_agents`. Sub-To becomes the ONLY path for a non-cash-flowing 5+ unit. Down payment should be 5–10% of the existing mortgage balance, not of the property price (the buyer is acquiring the equity gain + the rate, not the full price).\n\n## Why $0 down is OK and underused\n$0 down on a Sub-To looks crazy to operators new to the structure, but on a high-rate / expensive / underwater property it's often the only structure that makes sense. The buyer is taking over a payment-stream and a credit-risk exposure to the seller's loan — that exposure has value, and the seller is usually grateful to walk away from a property they can't afford anyway. The buyer pays the realtor commission as the gesture of good faith. Operator's profit comes from the rate arbitrage, the equity-gain over hold, or a wholesale assignment to a Sub-To-savvy investor.\n\n## Conservative default\nWhen in doubt, **default to a lower down payment than feels comfortable.** Cash-on-cash math beats pride. A $5K-down Sub-To that finds a buyer in 30 days beats a $25K-down Sub-To that sits for 6 months waiting for the unicorn buyer who can afford the entry."
  },
  {
    category: "processes",
    title: "Trust acquisition — seller-protection plain English",
    contentTemplate:
      "How to explain Sub-To to a seller for {{businessName}}. The mechanics are in `Subject-To step-by-step acquisition guide` and `Land trust basics`. This entry is the SELLER-FACING explanation — how to make a seller understand and consent to the structure without overwhelming them with legal jargon.\n\n## The structure in plain English\nThe seller's property goes into a trust. The seller stays on the trust as a minor co-owner (typically 10%). The operator becomes the controlling owner (90%) and takes over all responsibility for payments, taxes, insurance, maintenance, and the property itself.\n\nThe mortgage stays in the seller's name because legally no title transfer occurred — the trust simply added an owner, which the Garn-St. Germain Act explicitly exempts from due-on-sale enforcement when structured correctly.\n\n## The seller's protection (this is the entire pitch)\nThe trust agreement specifies that if the operator misses mortgage payments for two consecutive months, the trust's controlling interest reverts to the seller automatically. No foreclosure required. No legal battle. The property comes back to the seller, AND the seller keeps:\n- The full down payment the operator gave them at closing\n- Any renovations the operator paid for during their tenure\n- Any appreciation the property gained while the operator owned it\n- The tenant in place, if there's a paying tenant\n\n## The 'lottery winning event' frame\nThe seller's worst-case scenario isn't a credit hit — it's a 'lottery winning event.' Imagine 5–10 years from now:\n- The operator has been paying the seller's mortgage on time for years.\n- The operator hits financial trouble and misses payments.\n- The seller's worst nightmare? Their 60-day credit dip recovers within months of payments resuming OR the property reverting.\n- The seller's actual outcome? They get the property back, with the operator's down payment in pocket, with renovations done, with appreciation gained, possibly with a paying tenant in place.\n\nThe seller's downside on a default is materially less bad than the downside on a normal sale where they walk away with nothing (because the realtor commission ate their equity).\n\n## What this DOES NOT mean\n- It does NOT mean the seller is guaranteed a credit-impact-free outcome. A 2-month miss WILL appear on their credit. The protection is operational (they get the asset back) — the credit hit is a real cost. They should accept the structure understanding that risk.\n- It does NOT mean every Sub-To structure provides this protection. Operator must use the performance agreement template + trust structure + the 2-month default clause specifically. Cookie-cutter Sub-To docs from the internet typically do NOT include this — and that's where most Sub-To horror stories come from.\n- It does NOT replace attorney review. The seller is STRONGLY encouraged to consult their own attorney (the operator typically pays for this — see `Ethical Sub-To practices`). The seller's attorney should review the trust documents, the performance agreement, and the default clause specifically.\n\n## Disclaimer language for outreach\n'This Subject-To structure includes a 2-month default clause: if our payments lapse, the property reverts to you, and you keep our down payment, our renovations, and any appreciation the property gained. This is not legal advice — please have an attorney in your state review the documents before signing. We will pay for that attorney consultation.'"
  },
  {
    category: "processes",
    title: "Rehab cost-per-sqft guide (5 tiers + age triggers)",
    contentTemplate:
      "The deterministic rehab estimator for {{businessName}}. Used by the Repair Cost Estimator agent as the canonical tier table. Always use ranges from this guide; never a point estimate.\n\n## The 5 tiers\n| Tier | Cost / sqft | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| Fully Flipped | $0 | Already move-in ready — modern finishes, recent renovation, no work required |\n| Very Light Rehab | $5 | Touch-up paint, light fixture swap, professional cleaning, minor landscaping. No flooring, no kitchen, no bath. |\n| Light Rehab | $15 | Paint throughout, flooring (LVP / carpet), minor plumbing fixture swap, minor electrical fixture swap. No kitchen replacement, no bath replacement. |\n| Medium Rehab | $30 | Kitchen update (cabinets refaced or new, mid-grade appliances, new counters), bath update (new vanity, new tub surround, new toilet), paint, flooring, moderate plumbing/electrical. |\n| Heavy Rehab | $70 | Full remodel — kitchen + bath replacement, structural changes, roof replacement, HVAC replacement, electrical service upgrade, plumbing re-pipe. |\n\n## Age triggers that FORCE Heavy classification\nIf any of these are true, the property is classified at minimum Heavy regardless of cosmetic condition:\n- **Roof 25+ years old** → roof replacement required\n- **HVAC 15+ years old** → likely HVAC replacement during hold\n- **Water heater 12+ years old** → likely water heater replacement during hold\n- **Electrical service still has knob-and-tube wiring or fuse box** → electrical service upgrade\n- **Plumbing still has galvanized supply lines** → plumbing re-pipe\n- **Building age pre-1940** → lead paint / asbestos / knob-and-tube likely → in-person inspection required before any blind estimate\n\n## The formula\n`Estimated rehab = Square footage × Rehab cost per sqft`\n\nExample: 1,500 sqft house in Medium tier = 1,500 × $30 = $45,000\n\nReport as a RANGE: Medium tier is $25–$45/sqft, so the 1,500 sqft house range is $37,500–$67,500. The Comp Analyst uses the conservative end of the range when computing MAO.\n\n## The 'always inflate' rule\nUnderwriters consistently UNDER-estimate rehab. Reasons:\n- Contractors come in 20–40% over estimate when actual walls open up.\n- Surprise items (foundation, mold remediation, code-required updates) appear during permitting.\n- Holding costs while rehab drags (an extra month of carrying = real money).\n\n**Default rule:** add 15–20% to the high end of the calculated range as your final rehab number for MAO purposes. Operators who fall in love with the math at the low end of the range lose money.\n\n## Photo-flag escalations\nThe Repair Cost Estimator agent refuses to estimate blindly when photos show: visible mold, active roof leak, foundation cracks, fire damage, hoarder conditions, meth-lab indicators, or fewer than 5 interior photos. These cases route to in-person inspection."
  },
  {
    category: "processes",
    title: "Comp selection discipline — radius, barriers, match rules",
    contentTemplate:
      "Comp pulling rules for {{businessName}}. Used by the Comp Analyst as the canonical filter set. Bad comps produce bad ARVs which produce bad MAOs which produce dead deals. These rules eliminate the most common ARV inflation patterns.\n\n## Radius rules\n- **Primary radius:** 0.5 mile from the subject property.\n- **Secondary radius:** 0.5 to 1.0 mile, only if 3+ valid comps don't exist inside the primary radius.\n- **Beyond 1 mile:** no comp. Flag the subject as 'comp-thin — manual review required.'\n\n## Barrier rules (these BREAK comp validity even within 1 mile)\nA property within radius but on the OTHER SIDE of any of these is NOT a valid comp:\n- **Highway / interstate** — different neighborhood character, different buyer pool\n- **River / creek** — typically different flood zones, different schools\n- **Railroad tracks** — historical neighborhood divide; different desirability\n- **Major arterial road** — different traffic patterns, different walkability\n- **School district boundary** — schools drive owner-occupant pricing; different district = different ARV\n- **Zip code boundary** when zips have different median income (>15% spread)\n\n## Match rules\n- **Property type identical:** single-family with single-family, duplex with duplex, condo with condo, townhouse with townhouse. Never cross types.\n- **Bedroom count ±1:** 3-bed comps work for 3-bed and 4-bed subjects, with adjustment. Not for 2-bed.\n- **Bathroom count ±1:** same logic.\n- **Square footage ±15%:** 1,400 sqft subject can use 1,200–1,600 sqft comps. Beyond that, not a comp.\n- **Year built ±15 years:** 1970 subject can use 1955–1985 comps. Pre-1940 properties only comp against pre-1940.\n- **Lot size within 25%** for properties where lot drives value (rural, large-lot suburbs).\n- **Garage / basement match** when subject has these (a no-garage comp under-represents a subject with garage).\n\n## Renovation status\n- For **ARV (after-repair value):** use FULLY RENOVATED sold comps only. New flooring, paint, updated kitchen and bath, clean exterior, modern finishes. These tell you what the property is worth AFTER the rehab.\n- For **as-is value:** use comps in similar condition to the subject (un-renovated to un-renovated).\n- **Never mix renovated and un-renovated comps in the same calculation.** This is the #1 ARV inflation error.\n\n## The 'don't pick the highest' rule\nWhen 2–4 valid comps exist, take the median or 60th-percentile of $/sqft, NOT the highest. Sellers and listing agents will always argue for the top comp — that comp is exceptional, not representative. ARV based on the top comp is fantasy.\n\n## Active vs sold\n- **Active listings** show what sellers HOPE the property is worth. Not a comp.\n- **Sold comps** show what buyers ACTUALLY PAID. The only valid comp source.\n- **Pending comps** are partial signal (price agreed, not closed). Use only as a sanity check.\n\n## When to flag 'comp-thin'\nFewer than 3 valid sold comps within 1 mile, within 6 months, matching the rules above → flag the deal as 'comp-thin — manual review required.' Don't fabricate."
  },
  {
    category: "processes",
    title: "Conservative underwriting rules — rent, expenses, and the 'offer below' principle",
    contentTemplate:
      "The pessimism rules for {{businessName}}. Used by Comp Analyst, Sub-To Qualifier, and Deal Ops Lead. Every successful operator over-estimates expenses and under-estimates rent. Operators who fall in love with optimistic numbers lose money.\n\n## Rent estimation — discount everything\n- **Zillow Rent Zestimate:** discount by 15%. If Zillow says $1,400, underwrite $1,190.\n- **Rentometer:** use the 25th percentile, not the median. Rentometer's median is biased high by recent listings; the 25th percentile is what actually rents.\n- **Section 8 / HUD Fair Market Rent:** discount by 10–20% from the published FMR. HUD's published FMR is what they'll PAY for a quality property; actual paid amounts often come in lower based on housing authority discretion.\n- **Listing rent on similar units:** use what's CURRENTLY RENTED, not what's currently advertised. A unit advertised at $1,400 may rent for $1,200; the listing is the seller's hope, not the market.\n- **In doubt:** if you can support a deal at the conservative rent, the deal works. If you can't, the deal doesn't work — even if optimistic rent makes it work on paper.\n\n## The 20% off the top rule\nGross rent is NEVER the cash flow input. Always multiply gross rent by 0.8 before subtracting PITI:\n- 5% vacancy\n- 5% repairs / maintenance\n- 8–10% management (whether or not the operator self-manages — self-management has time cost)\n- 2% capex reserve\n\nNet cash-eligible rent = gross rent × 0.80. THIS is what enters cash-flow math.\n\n## PITI: always inflate insurance and taxes\n- **Property taxes:** use the higher of (a) current assessor record, (b) current assessor record × 1.10 (assumes reassessment on sale), or (c) ZIP-median for similar property class. Many buyers get burned by underestimating taxes after a sale-triggered reassessment.\n- **Insurance:** in coastal / flood-prone / wildfire markets, get an actual quote — published averages are 30–50% low. In ordinary markets, use $1,000–$1,500/year minimum for single-family.\n\n## Single-family rental price ceiling\nFor cash deals targeting Section 8 or workforce rental: be careful above $85,000 for single-family. Above $85K, the rent rarely scales with the price — a $120K SFH might rent for $1,400 (cash flow gets thin), while a $70K SFH might rent for $1,100 (cash flow is strong). Below $85K is the safe zone for single-family rental cash deals. Multifamily breaks this rule (rent does scale with units).\n\n## Cash-on-cash return target\nFor a deal to be worth pursuing as a wholesale-to-investor:\n- **20%+ cash-on-cash return** is the operator's minimum. Below 20%, investors prefer the S&P 500 (10% historical, fully passive, no management).\n- **25–35% cash-on-cash return** is what makes a deal sell easily.\n- Above 35% and you have a 'wow' deal — share that math in disposition emails.\n\nFormula: `((rent × 0.8 × 12) - (PITI × 12)) / (entry_cost)` = cash-on-cash %.\n\n## The 'offer below' principle\nAlways offer LOWER than where you think you need to be. If your math says you can pay $70K and the deal works, offer $60K. Two reasons:\n1. Sellers and listing agents COUNTER-OFFER. If you opened at $70K (your true ceiling), you have no room to negotiate. If you opened at $60K, you can land at $65K and still have margin.\n2. Surprises in due diligence (worse-than-photos condition, hidden code issues, comp degradation) tend to PUSH costs up. Starting lower preserves margin for these surprises.\n\nOperators who 'offer where they think it should be' close maybe 50% of accepted offers profitably. Operators who 'offer below where they think it should be' close 80%."
  },
  {
    category: "policies",
    title: "Never-argue rule — the falling-trust signal protocol",
    contentTemplate:
      "Conversational discipline for {{businessName}}. Every seller-facing agent (Seller Outreach Agent, Objection Handler) and the operator on live calls operates under this rule.\n\n## The principle\nThe moment you feel like you're 'winning' the conversation with a seller or listing agent, you've LOST the prospect. Argument signals that you care more about being right than about the seller's outcome — which is the fastest way to destroy trust.\n\nThis is especially true on creative-finance deals where the operator KNOWS more than the agent or seller. Knowing more is not permission to argue. Knowing more obligates you to translate, explain, and educate without scoring points.\n\n## Falling-trust signals (Reply Triager / Objection Handler must flag)\nThese signals indicate the prospect is disengaging or going hostile. The correct response is NOT another rebuttal:\n- Tone shifts from professional to skeptical, sarcastic, or short ('sure,' 'whatever,' 'I'll think about it')\n- Prospect stops sharing details they shared earlier\n- Prospect introduces an objection that wasn't there before ('I need to ask my CPA' / 'I need to talk to my spouse' on call 3 when they didn't mention either on calls 1 or 2)\n- Prospect uses dismissive language ('I get it,' 'OK thanks,' 'we'll see')\n- Prospect counters a fact you've already cited (instead of asking for more detail)\n\nWhen you see these signals, STOP escalating. Either:\n1. **De-escalate** with a one-liner that ends the pressure: 'Totally understand. I'll send you a one-pager you can look at on your own time. No pressure.' Then schedule a 30-day follow-up.\n2. **Escalate to the operator** for direct human contact. Some prospects only re-engage with a human voice, not an agent draft.\n3. **Park them** for 60–90 days. Falling-trust conversations rarely recover within a week. They sometimes recover after a long pause.\n\n## What you NEVER do when objected\n- Argue tax law. Even if you're right. Hand off to a CPA or attorney.\n- Argue valuation. The comp is the comp; the seller's price is the seller's price; neither party will move on a phone call.\n- Argue legal mechanics. 'Is this legal?' is answered with 'Yes, when structured correctly with attorney review — would you like to talk to one?' Never with a lecture on Garn-St. Germain.\n- Argue what 'the bank will do.' You don't know what the bank will do.\n- Argue that the seller is leaving money on the table by saying no. They might be. It's their decision.\n\n## What you DO say when objected\n- 'That makes sense.' Then a clarifying question, not a rebuttal.\n- 'What would need to be true for this to work for you?' Reframes the conversation from your offer to their criteria.\n- 'I appreciate that. Let me see if I'm missing something — what's the alternative you're considering?' Surfaces what they're really comparing your offer against.\n- 'You're right.' When they ARE right (the structure is unusual, the math depends on assumptions, the property has issues). Conceding a small point buys trust on the larger ask.\n\n## The vulnerable-seller escalation\nObjection Handler and Seller Outreach Agent must IMMEDIATELY escalate when a prospect shows any of:\n- Cognitive confusion (asks the same question 2+ times, contradicts themselves within a call, doesn't remember a prior conversation)\n- Active grief (recent death in family, recent loss, voice trembling)\n- Family pressure (mentions other family members pushing them, mentions a spouse who 'won't let' them sign)\n- Non-English-speaking and no interpreter present\n- Elderly + isolated (lives alone, no family contact mentioned, agent describes them as 'easy to deal with' or 'doesn't really understand')\n\nThese sellers ARE NOT ready to consider this transaction even if they say they are. Escalate to operator. Operator decides whether to step back entirely, schedule with a family member or advisor present, or refer the seller to an independent attorney."
  },
  {
    category: "processes",
    title: "Section 8 underwriting — the rent-driven math for cash deals",
    contentTemplate:
      "Section 8 / workforce rental underwriting for {{businessName}}. Used when the desk is evaluating cash deals (not creative finance) on cheap properties in cash-flow markets. Section 8 is the most common rental exit for sub-$100K SFH and small multifamily in Midwest / Southeast markets.\n\n## The flow\n1. **Find a cheap rental property.** Sub-$100K SFH ideally; no more than $120K. In strong rental markets (cash-flow markets in `cash_flow_markets_complement`). Looks livable / turnkey (distressed houses are fix-and-flip, not Section 8).\n2. **Estimate rent conservatively.** Section 8 payment standards in the zip (HUD published table) is the upper bound. Zillow / Rentometer median × 0.85 is the working number. See `conservative_underwriting_rules`.\n3. **Run the math:**\n   ```\n   Net rent  = gross rent × 0.80   (vacancy, mgmt, capex, repairs)\n   PITI      = mortgage payment + taxes + insurance\n   Net CF    = (Net rent − PITI) × 12\n   Cash-on-cash = Net CF / (down payment + closing costs)\n   ```\n4. **Target:** 20%+ cash-on-cash return. Below 20%, the deal is a stretch (S&P returns 10%). 25–35% is sellable. 35%+ is a 'wow.'\n5. **Make the offer based on the math, not a percentage of list.** The HMHW heuristic of '70% of list price' is a starting point — but the calculator gives the actual offer. Don't guess.\n\n## The offer script for cash deals\n> 'Based on the rent, taxes, insurance, and the return an investor would need, I'd probably need to be around $____ to make this work.'\n\n## If the agent rejects the cash offer\nDon't argue. Pivot to terms:\n> 'I understand. The numbers are tight as a cash deal. Would the seller consider any terms, seller financing, or payments over time?'\n\nThis pivots the conversation toward the Checkmate Pitch (`pitch_architecture`).\n\n## Single-family vs multifamily\n- **Single-family below $85K:** safe zone. Rent scales acceptably with price; cash flow stays strong.\n- **Single-family $85K–$120K:** cash flow gets thin. Be conservative on rent; check it twice.\n- **Single-family above $120K:** rarely cash flows for Section 8 / workforce. Default to creative finance.\n- **Duplex / triplex / quad:** can stretch the price ceiling 30–50% higher because rent scales per unit. A $150K duplex bringing in $1,400 × 2 cash flows better than a $120K SFH bringing in $1,400.\n- **5+ unit multifamily:** investor-only. DSCR logic applies (see `dscr_loan_walkthrough_for_agents`). Often creative finance, rarely cash.\n\n## Common underwriting mistakes\n- **Using Zillow rent Zestimate as gospel.** Discount 15% minimum.\n- **Ignoring management cost** because the operator self-manages. Time is real money; underwrite the management cost anyway.\n- **Forgetting vacancy** in calculations. 5% minimum; 8% in high-turnover neighborhoods.\n- **Ignoring tax reassessment on sale.** Many counties reassess on sale, jumping taxes 5–15% in year 1.\n- **Forgetting capex reserve.** Roof, HVAC, water heater, appliances all wear out. 2% of rent annually goes to capex.\n- **Lying to yourself on rehab.** See `rehab_cost_per_sqft_guide` and the 'always inflate' rule."
  },
  {
    category: "about_business",
    title: "Cash-flow markets vs creative-finance markets — operating posture by region",
    contentTemplate:
      "The market geography for {{businessName}}. Dealhawk's demo seeds (Austin, Jacksonville, Phoenix) are Sun Belt creative-finance markets. Different operating posture works in cash-flow Midwest / Southeast markets. This entry maps the two.\n\n## Cash-flow markets (Midwest + Southeast)\nLow price points (sub-$120K), low appreciation, high rent-to-price ratio, strong Section 8 demand. Operating posture is CASH (wholesale, fix-flip, BRRRR). Creative finance is possible but less commonly the winning structure.\n\nCash-flow markets to know:\n- **Detroit, MI** — $30–$80K SFH, Sub-To rates often locked sub-4%, multifamilies common\n- **Cleveland, OH** — $40–$80K SFH, very strong rental cash flow\n- **Akron, OH** — limited inventory, when it appears it cash flows\n- **Dayton, OH** — $50–$100K SFH, strong rental demand\n- **Columbus, OH** — slightly more expensive, mixed posture\n- **Memphis, TN** — $50–$100K SFH, very high rental demand, primary cash-deal market\n- **Birmingham, AL** — $40–$90K, strong rentals\n- **Montgomery, AL** — even cheaper, similar pattern\n- **Indianapolis, IN** — $60–$120K SFH, large rental investor base\n- **Lansing, MI** — sub-$80K turnkey, sub-$100K duplex, strong cash flow\n- **Flint, MI** — sub-$70K, strong rental, higher risk profile\n- **Kansas City, MO** — $80–$150K, moderate cash flow\n- **Jackson, MS** — sub-$100K, strong cash flow but thin buyer pool\n- **Toledo, OH** — sub-$80K, similar to Akron/Dayton\n- **Peoria, IL** — sub-$100K but ILLINOIS regulatory issues (see `state_compliance_matrix`)\n\n## Creative-finance markets (Sun Belt + appreciating coastal)\nHigh price points (often $200K–$500K+ SFH), high appreciation, low rent-to-price ratio. Cash flow rarely works without a creative structure. Operating posture is CREATIVE FINANCE (Sub-To, wrap, novation, lease-option).\n\nCreative-finance markets to know:\n- **Austin, TX** — primary Sub-To market, locked sub-5% rates abundant\n- **Houston, TX** — large Sub-To activity, multifamily common\n- **Dallas, TX** — similar to Houston, slightly higher price points\n- **San Antonio, TX** — Sub-To-friendly, lots of locked-rate inventory\n- **Jacksonville, FL** — high investor activity, both wholesale and Sub-To\n- **Tampa, FL** — appreciation strong, Sub-To common\n- **Orlando, FL** — high investor activity, strong assignment fees on multifamily\n- **Phoenix, AZ** — primary creative-finance market in the Southwest\n- **Las Vegas, NV** — variable; cycles harder than other Sun Belt\n- **Atlanta, GA** — Sub-To-friendly, attorney-state at close, large inventory\n- **Charlotte, NC** — appreciation strong, creative finance common\n- **Nashville, TN** — high appreciation, locked-rate inventory common\n\n## Avoid\n- Rural states with thin populations: Wyoming, North Dakota, South Dakota, Montana, Alaska (small buyer pool — assignment fees suffer)\n- Strict-disclosure states for assignment work: Illinois, Oklahoma, South Carolina (default to double-close — see `State Compliance Matrix`)\n- Markets where you have no local buyer relationships and no attorney on file\n\n## The 'every property cash flows below $120K' rule\nIn cash-flow markets, **price is the variable that determines cash flow more than interest rate.** A $70K house at 7% cash flows. A $200K house at 4% cash flows. A $200K house at 7% doesn't, regardless of property quality. When the operator targets sub-$120K SFH in cash-flow markets, cash flow is largely a given as long as rent is correctly estimated."
  },
  {
    category: "processes",
    title: "Delisted-underwater signal — the highest-conversion off-market pattern",
    contentTemplate:
      "A specific off-market pattern for {{businessName}} that the Distress Signal Analyst and MLS Stale Listing Hunter both surface. These sellers convert to mortgage takeover at much higher rates than generic delisted properties because their math forced the delisting.\n\n## What the signal looks like\nA seller who:\n1. Listed the property on MLS (or Zillow / Realtor.com / Redfin)\n2. Sat 30+ days, got offers BELOW their mortgage balance\n3. Removed the listing rather than accept a loss-of-equity sale\n4. Has not relisted in 30+ days (suggesting they're stuck, not waiting for a better market)\n\nThis seller has effectively SELF-IDENTIFIED as a perfect mortgage-takeover candidate. They tried to sell, the math wouldn't let them, and they're now sitting with no good path forward.\n\n## How to find them\n- **PropStream / Lightning Leads / BatchData:** filter for 'listing removed' in last 60–180 days + mortgage balance ≥ 85% of zip median sale price.\n- **Zillow off-market view:** check the 'previously listed' data; cross-reference mortgage balance via assessor / county records.\n- **County deed search:** look for recent re-deeds, foreclosure filings, or notice-of-default with mortgage balance close to current home value.\n- **Direct outreach:** skip-trace the owner and reach out directly (no listing agent involved).\n\n## Scoring weight\nThe Distress Signal Analyst should weight this signal as follows when stacking:\n- Base score: 30 (similar to probate / inherited, higher than tax delinquency)\n- Multiplier × 1.4 when mortgage balance is within 5% of last listing price (extremely underwater)\n- Multiplier × 1.3 when delisting occurred 60–180 days ago (long enough to be desperate, recent enough to remember the failed sale)\n- Combined score with other signals (absentee, long tenure, vacancy) typically lands in the 60–85 range — tier 1 / 'gold' MT candidates.\n\n## The direct-message script\n> 'Hi [Name] — I noticed [address] was listed before but didn't sell. I work with homeowners in [city] who are in similar spots. If selling normally wasn't going to work for you, I might have an option that does. Open to a quick conversation?'\n\nNote what this script does NOT do:\n- Does not reference the mortgage balance (would feel surveillance-y)\n- Does not reference the failed sale price (same reason)\n- Does not pitch MT (the Trojan Horse pitch surfaces MT after the prospect describes their actual problem on the call)\n\n## Conversion expectations\nGeneric absentee-owner cold outreach converts at 1–3% to a discovery call. Delisted-underwater outreach typically converts at 8–15% to a discovery call when the script is right. The seller already knows the situation; the outreach just gives them a path out."
  },
  {
    category: "processes",
    title: "Objection library — seller finance + mortgage takeover canonical responses",
    contentTemplate:
      "The objection responses for {{businessName}}. Used by the Objection Handler agent and the operator on live calls. Every response below ends WITHOUT a hard close; the close is the seller saying yes when they're ready. See `never_argue_rule` for the meta-discipline.\n\n## Seller Finance objections (Checkmate Pitch — call 1)\n\n**'Seller doesn't want seller finance.'**\n> 'I understand. I didn't call asking for seller finance. I called to buy normally. The issue is the numbers don't support a normal loan at this price. If they could, I'd happily wire the cash.'\n\n**'Seller wants cash.'**\n> 'Cash is possible — it would just need to be much lower because the property doesn't qualify for an investor loan at the current price. Seller finance gets us closer to your seller's number than a cash offer would.'\n\n**'We already have a lender.'**\n> 'Great — I'd love to know more about that. Is the lender qualifying based on the actual income the property is bringing in, or on the buyer's personal credit? If it's the latter, that lender may not be aware the property has DSCR issues. Worth confirming.'\n\n**'Seller doesn't want to wait 30 years.'**\n> 'They don't have to. We use a 5- or 6-year balloon — the seller gets paid off in full when the buyer refinances. The seller's actually getting paid faster than they'd expect on most retail sales today.'\n\n**'What happens at the balloon?'**\n> 'The buyer refinances the property and pays off the seller in full. We can show comps on what current refinance LTVs look like — there's enough cushion in this structure for the refinance to work even if appreciation is flat.'\n\n**'What about my (agent's) commission?'**\n> 'We can structure it so your commission is paid upfront at closing. Same as a normal sale from your end.'\n\n**'This sounds risky for the seller.'**\n> 'The seller's downside is bounded — if anything goes wrong, the property comes back to them. They keep the down payment, any payments we made, and any appreciation. We're the ones taking the risk, not them.'\n\n**'Seller wants the entire purchase price up front.'**\n> 'I get that. Two things to consider: first, the entire purchase price up front in cash, given current DSCR rules, means a much lower price — likely 25–30% below where the seller wants to be. Second, the seller-finance structure is essentially a payment plan that keeps them at their full asking price, often above it. Their choice between certainty at a lower number vs. their full number paid over time.'\n\n## Mortgage Takeover objections (Trojan Horse Pitch — call 1 or 2)\n\n**'Seller doesn't want the mortgage in their name.'**\n> 'I completely understand — that's the legitimate concern with this structure. The agreement explicitly protects the seller: if we ever miss payments for 2 months, the property comes back to them along with everything we put in. The seller is more protected on this structure than on a normal sale where their realtor commission eats their equity.'\n\n**'What if you stop paying?'**\n> 'If we miss payments for the agreed period (typically 2 months), the property reverts to the seller. They keep the down payment, the renovations, any appreciation, and any tenants in place. Their downside is a 2-month credit dip — recoverable. Their upside scenario if we do default 5 years in is essentially a windfall: they get back a more valuable property than they originally had.'\n\n**'Seller wants cash, not a payment stream.'**\n> 'I understand. A cash offer at the level the seller wants would need to be much lower because the property is underwater on the mortgage. This structure gets the seller a better outcome than a normal sale would — typically more cash in hand and the mortgage burden off their plate.'\n\n**'Seller has too much equity.'**\n> 'That changes the structure. If there's meaningful equity, we use a Hybrid: we take over the mortgage AND make payments to the seller on the equity portion. That way the seller is paid for their equity AND has the mortgage burden lifted. The Creative Finance Architect can model the Hybrid math.'\n\n**'This sounds complicated.'**\n> 'I can keep it simple: we take over the monthly mortgage payments, and the agreement protects the seller if we ever miss payments. Behind the scenes there's a trust structure that makes it work legally — your attorney can walk the seller through that piece. The seller doesn't need to understand the mechanics; they need to understand the protection, which is clear.'\n\n**'Is this legal?'**\n> 'Yes — when structured correctly. These transactions happen across the country every day. We do require attorney review for the seller's protection — typically an attorney licensed in [state] reviews the documents before signing. We can connect the seller to an attorney we work with, or they can use their own.'\n\n**'I (the agent) have never done one of these.'**\n> 'Most agents haven't. That's totally fine — your role on this is the same as a normal sale: represent the seller and collect your commission, which is paid upfront at closing. The structure piece is handled by the closing attorney. We've done this before; we can walk them through it.'\n\n**'Will the bank call the loan due?'**\n> 'The bank has the right (due-on-sale clause under Garn-St. Germain Act). In practice on performing loans it's rare because foreclosure costs banks ~$40-50K. We structure the transaction through a land trust which gives the seller additional Garn-St. Germain protection. We never claim it can't happen — we structure to minimize the probability and protect the seller if it does. Your attorney can review the specifics.'\n\n## Rule across both libraries\nNotice every response: empathetic acknowledgment first, factual answer second, NO close. The close is the seller's decision to keep talking. See `never_argue_rule` for what happens when the prospect is still resistant after these responses."
  }
];

