        contentTemplate: `# {{businessName}} — Pitch Architecture (operator SOP)

The desk's conversational architecture. Read once. Reference on every live call. The Seller Outreach Agent and Objection Handler are trained against this document.

## The core principle

**Nobody wants seller finance. Nobody wants their mortgage taken over.**

If you open a call with "will the seller seller-finance?" or "can I take over your mortgage?", the listing agent rejects you 95% of the time. Listing agents protect their clients from anything that looks complicated or unusual, especially structures they themselves don't understand.

The operator's job is to call about a NORMAL purchase, walk the agent through why every normal path fails on this specific listing, and let creative finance arrive as the SOLUTION TO A PROBLEM THE AGENT JUST NAMED.

Two near-identical moves. Same skeleton. Different leverage.

---

## Checkmate Pitch — for seller finance on properties that don't cash flow

Use when: the property is investor-only (multifamily 5+ units, or SFH where rent < 1% of price), the seller wants their asking price, and the property has been sitting because no investor loan qualifies at that price.

### The call flow

**Step 1: Open at or near asking.**

> "Hey, I'm calling about [address]. I may be interested at or near asking. I just need to understand how the numbers work."

You are NOT lying. You ARE interested in the property. You are NOT yet committed to a price. The agent should hear "warm buyer who needs to qualify a few things."

**Step 2: Ask the income question.**

> "What is the property currently bringing in per month? Is that actual or projected?"

Always anchor on ACTUAL rent. Projected rent is the seller's hope, not the market's reality.

**Step 3: Demonstrate the DSCR fail.**

> "Based on what it's bringing in, a normal investor loan payment on this price would be ~$[X]. After taxes, insurance, vacancy, repairs, and management, the property loses money each month. A DSCR-style investor loan legally cannot qualify a borrower on negative cash flow — that's a predatory loan. Are you seeing the same on your end?"

This educates the agent. Most listing agents don't know why their investment listing isn't selling. When you walk them through DSCR, you become the educator. Agents trust educators.

**Step 4: Walk the three buyer types out the door.**

- "Loan buyer? Can't qualify at this price because of DSCR."
- "Cash buyer? Would need a 25–30% discount because the stock market returns 10% passively. Buying real estate that requires management for less return is irrational. So a cash offer would be way below the seller's number."
- "Lowball buyer? Sounds like you've already gotten those offers and the seller said no."

After this, the agent should be quiet. Their three default paths just got walked out the door.

**Step 5: Present seller finance as the only remaining path.**

> "The only way I see to get close to your seller's number is to structure payments. I could offer [price at or above asking], [down payment] down, monthly [payment], with a balloon in [5 or 6] years."

You can offer ABOVE asking with 0% interest, OR offer asking with interest. Not both. Pick one.

**Step 6: Lubricate with the commission line.**

> "And we'll make sure your commission is paid upfront at closing — same as a normal sale from your end."

This sentence does more work than any other in the pitch. Most agent objections to seller finance evaporate the moment their commission is secured.

---

## Trojan Horse Pitch — for mortgage takeover on low-equity properties

Use when: the property's mortgage balance is close to or above the likely sale price, the seller is underwater or near-underwater, the seller has delisted or is sitting with no path forward.

### The call flow

**Step 1: Open with a cash offer 12–15% below list.**

> "Hey, I'm calling about [address]. Would the seller consider $[X]?" (where X is meaningfully below list — usually 12–15% below for low-equity sellers)

You are NOT trying to get this offer accepted. You are trying to surface the mortgage problem.

**Step 2: Wait for the rejection.**

Most listing agents on underwater properties reject below-asking with a tell:

> "No, the seller can't go that low because they have a mortgage they need to cover."

That tell is the unlock. The agent just volunteered the seller's exact problem.

**Step 3: Pivot to the mortgage-takeover solution.**

> "Oh — if the mortgage is close to the list price, would they consider letting us take over the debt instead? I can offer the seller $[X] to walk away, pay your commission upfront, and take over the monthly payments."

You are offering MT as a solution to a problem the agent just named. The frame is "you told me the seller's problem; here's how I solve it."

**Step 4: Soft the structure question.**

> "Behind the scenes there's a trust structure that protects the seller — if our payments ever miss, the property reverts to them along with the down payment and any improvements. Your closing attorney can review the mechanics. The seller doesn't need to understand the legal details; they need to understand they're protected, which they are."

DO NOT explain trust acquisition in detail on call 1. Overloading the agent kills the call. Save mechanics for call 2.

---

## Rules across both pitches

### 1. Never argue

The moment you feel like you're winning the conversation, you've lost the prospect. See "Never-argue rule" in the KB.

When you hit a falling-trust signal (skeptical tone, withdrawal, dismissive language), STOP escalating. Either de-escalate with a low-pressure close ("I'll send a one-pager you can review at your own pace") or schedule a 30-day follow-up. Some prospects re-engage; others don't. You can't win them back with one more rebuttal.

### 2. Always mention the agent's commission is paid upfront

This is the single most important sentence on either pitch. Listing agents protect commissions. Once that's secured, they advocate for creative structures with the seller.

### 3. Never claim what you can't deliver

- Never promise the bank won't call the loan due. (Garn-St. Germain → rare on performing loans, but not impossible.)
- Never promise the seller's credit will be protected. (A 2-month miss WILL show up on credit if it happens.)
- Never commit to a specific closing date before title search.
- Never promise specific tax outcomes.

### 4. Never reference the seller's filing

- Pre-foreclosure: no mention of the NOD.
- Probate: no mention of the probate filing.
- Divorce: no mention of the divorce filing.
- Delisted-underwater: no mention of the failed sale price or the mortgage balance.

The seller should never feel surveilled. Even if all the data is public, surveillance kills trust.

### 5. Honor dealMode

In \`research\` mode this is the operator's playbook only — agents draft and rehearse, agents do not place outreach calls. In \`outreach\` mode the pitch is live. In \`contract\` mode binding agreements are generated; attorney review is strongly recommended for Sub-To and statute-heavy states.

---

## When the pitch fails

It will fail often. Expected close rate from a cold listing agent: 5–15% to a discovery conversation, 1–5% to a signed contract. These are SIGNAL-RICH calls; the operator is not closing every one.

When a pitch fails:
- Log the outcome in the deal pipeline (lead status: "agent rejected" / "seller rejected" / "discovery scheduled" / "follow-up 30/60/90").
- Update the Follow-Up Sequencer cadence.
- Move to the next call. The volume of attempts is what produces the close rate.

The pitch architecture turns 1-in-200 cold calls into 1-in-25 conversions. Volume is still the input. Architecture is the multiplier.

---

## Source

Pitch architecture rolled in from the Hold My Hand Wholesale (HMHW) courses by Richard Taylor — cash, seller finance, and mortgage takeover. The skeleton is HMHW's "Checkmate" and "Trojan Horse" frames; the trust acquisition seller-protection language, DSCR walkthrough specifics, and rate × price matrix are integrated with {{businessName}}'s own state matrix, never-argue rule, and ethical Sub-To practices already in the KB.
`
